Fear no more the heat o” the sun Nor the furious winter's rages;

Thou thy worldly task hast done, Home art gone, and ta'en thy wages

Golden lads and girls all must,

ÅAs chimney-sweepers, come to dust.

Fear no more the frown o? the great;

Thou art past the tyrant's stroke; Care no more to clothe and eat;

To thee the reed is as the oak: The sceptre, learning, physic, must All follow this, and come to dust.

Fear no more the lightning-flash Nor the all-dreaded thunder-stone Fer not slander, censure rash; Thou hast finish”*d joy and moan: All lovers young, all lovers must Consign to thee, and come to dust.
